pullRequest.body:
Include the following lemmas on equivalence of `MulRingNorms`. 
```lean
lemma f_of_abs_eq_f (x : ‚Ñ§) : f (Int.natAbs x) = f x
lemma NormRat_eq_on_Int_iff_eq_on_Nat : (‚àÄ n : ‚Ñï , f n = g n) ‚Üî (‚àÄ n : ‚Ñ§ , f n = g n)
lemma NormRat_eq_iff_eq_on_Nat : (‚àÄ n : ‚Ñï , f n = g n) ‚Üî f = g
lemma NormRat_equiv_iff_equiv_on_Nat : (‚àÉ c : ‚Ñù, 0 < c ‚àß (‚àÄ n : ‚Ñï , (f n)^c = g n)) ‚Üî f.equiv g
```

nodes.body: I read the statements. They are useful within a proof of Ostrowski but I am not sure they are really interesting besides that. I wonder whether they could be included in a Ostrowski file, as private lemmas.

> I read the statements. They are useful within a proof of Ostrowski but I am not sure they are really interesting besides that. I wonder whether they could be included in a Ostrowski file, as private lemmas.

I agree with moving them to a file specific to the rationals (but I am not sure about making them private lemmas).

### PR summary

#### Import changes

No significant changes to the import graph

`+ eq_on_Nat_iff_eq`

I have added a very minor golfing in one proof; apart from this, please modify the references to adhere to `mathlib` style, expecially because this creates links in the documentation website. After that, I think the PR will be ready to go.
Here I think `f` should be explicit.
Once on has Ostrowski, one knows that if there is n such that f n \neq 1 and g n \neq 1, then f and g are equivalent.
Hi! Yes, and we use this Lemma in Ostrowski's proof. :)
Where is this variable used?
You're right, we never use it here. But seeing the next suggestion we can use it :D
Since it is only used in that lemma, I would put it as an argument there instead of as a variable.
That makes sense!
This should be renamed. Maybe to `MulRingNorm.apply_natAbs_eq`?
Also, this should work for `f : MulRingNorm R` over any ring `R`.
I like your suggestion. As for the generalization to any R, then that'd justify the variable R :D
You probably want to open the `Int` namespace.
Done
I am not sure about the name of this and the next two lemmas.
Any suggestion is welcome!
Maybe they could be moved to the `Rat.MulRingNorm` namespace. So this would become `Rat.MulRingNorm.eq_on_Int_iff_eq_on_Nat`, and similarly for the other lemmas.
Uhmm sorry for the silly question, but how do I do it? Do I move the theorems to that file or is there some command to do it in this file? Sorry again üòÖ
I think it works like a section: you open it with `namespace Rat.MulRingNorm` and close it with `end Rat.MulRingNorm`.

Thank you. I did it, and now simp doesn't recognise the files in the "Int" namespace, so I had to give it the full names. Is that okay?

Oh, no, I see some merge conflicts! ...Help? üòÖ
I am fixing it.
(this is very easy, since it is in a file you don't care about)
Done (the bot is not super fast to remove the label, but it will do it). Don't forget to get a new cache after pulling.

I think `NormRat` should not be part of these three lemma names (since they are already in the `Rat.MulRingNorm` space). So the names should be `eq_on_Int_iff_eq_on_Nat`, `eq_iff_eq_on_Nat` and `equiv_iff_equiv_on_Nat`.
Up to this change, the PR looks good to me, but I think it should be approved by someone not involved with the project.

Changes implemented!

Nirvana, could you resolve all conversations for which you have already implemented the changes? 
Also, I still think that the results specific to norms on the rationals should be moved to a different file, as suggested by Antoine.

Yeah, sorry I didn't know I could do that! (first PR, so much to learn).
I'll make a new file and of course suggestions on different names and stuff are welcome!
There is a working file now, but I suppose I should write some sort of introduction, right?

If I understood @AntoineChambert-Loir right, he was suggesting to include the three lemmas about the rationals directly in the Ostrowski file. I guess it should be called "Ostrowski", but where should it go?  In Analysis/Normed/Ring/Seminorm? Somewhere in NumberTheory?
I would say in the number theory folder.
Moved!
I suppose that things that only work for Q and more general results will be put in different files once we start Ostrowski for number fields, but let's take care of Q first. :)
